            "answer_text": "If by end of the world you understand a \u201creset\u201d of the world through a global catastrophe, then yes: Aum Shimrikyo, led by Shoko Asahara.  Presenting itself as a mixture of Christianity, Buddhism, yoga and communism, Aum promised spiritual healing, positive thinking, body healing, improving intelligence and even superpowers. This propaganda helped the \u201creligion of the elites,\u201d as it was dubbed, attract many brilliant youngsters from top universities and to enjoy the fastest growth in the history of Japan: from dozens of members in 1984 to almost 9,000 in Japan and over 40,000 worldwide in 1995. But behind closed doors the members were guinea pigs for experiments and rituals that included the use of hallucinogens, brutal ascetic practices and brainwashing shock therapies. With thousands of supporters and millions of dollars at hand, the megalomaniac ambitions of Asahara, this blind messiah, briefly headed toward politics. In 1990 he and other 24 members ran in the general elections for a seat in the Japanese Parliament. It was a humiliating failure which profoundly hurt Asahara\u2019s ego and made the philosophy of the organization very hostile. Asahara accused the government of manipulating the elections, said that the United States was the apocalyptic beast that would attack Japan, it would trigger the Third World War and the world would end in 1997 engulfed in a nuclear Armageddon. The only way to survive was to join the sect, which posterior to the conflagration was supposed to establish the Millennium. From 1989 to 1995 an Aum elite of several hundred people, under Asahara\u2019s guidance and approval, conducted extortions, assassinations and terrorist attacks. Anyone who was seen as a threat became a living target for the fanatic arm of the sect. Such actions attracted the attention of the authorities, which prepared a simultaneous raid at several Aum locations. It is not known if Asahara ordered the sarin gas attack to deflect the attention of the authorities from his cult or to overthrow the Japanese government and to trigger the Third World War. In any case, on the morning of March 20, 1995, Aum members released sarin gas in a coordinated attack on five lines of the Tokyo subway, killing 12 commuters, seriously injuring 54 and affecting around 1,000. Then, on the 5th of May, when most of the leaders of the sect had already been arrested and others were on the run, a burning paper was found in a toilet from Shinjuku station in Tokyo, the busiest in the world. The paper was imbued with hydrogen cyanide which, had it not been extinguished in time, would have released enough gas in the ventilation system to potentially kill thousands of people. And on the 16th of May, on the day Asahara was captured, a parcel bomb was sent to the Tokyo city hall in an attempt to kill the governor, who had declared that he would revoke Aum\u2019s status as a religion. It may sound cynical, but it is likely that the subway attack prevented an even more devastating incident. Only after the annihilation of the sect did Japanese society come to see Asahara\u2019s real ambitions. He used the financial power of the organization to directly cause the end of the world. At the sect\u2019s locations the authorities found millions of dollars, cells with prisoners, evidence about previous assassinations and an arsenal of biochemical weapons: Ebola cultures, the sarin agent, advanced VX agents of neuronal stimulation, killing diseases such as Q fever and anthrax, the LSD drug, methamphetamine and an unsuccessful form of truth serum. In terms of firearms, Aum tried to assemble its own line of gun production, acquired massive amounts of explosives, a Russian military helicopter and even tried purchasing an atomic bomb.  Check these sources for detailed information: Aum Shinrikyo - Wikipedia Robert Jay Lifton, Destroying the World to Save It: Aum Shinrikyo, Apocalyptic Violence, and the New Global Terrorism (New York: Henry Holt & Co., 2000). Ian Reader, Religious Violence in Contemporary Japan: The Case of Aum Shinrikyo (Honolulu: University of Hawai\u2019i Press, 2000). Best.  www.reasonandreligion.org ",
